&gt;&gt; David: How not to buy a car.

00:00:26.960 --> 00:00:28.862
This is your Marketplace.

00:00:31.864 --> 00:00:34.466
&gt;&gt; David: Jenny's shopping
for her first vehicle.

00:00:34.466 --> 00:00:40.673 align:start position:0%
The biggest purchase of her life
and cost is her main concern.

00:00:40.673 --> 00:00:43.275
&gt;&gt; Ya, I'm just
looking for cars.

00:00:43.275 --> 00:00:44.276
&gt;&gt; Oh, okay, sure.

00:00:44.276 --> 00:00:45.511
&gt;&gt; I'm looking
for a smaller car.

00:00:45.511 --> 00:00:48.114
I'm just looking for a
little commuter car.

00:00:48.114 --> 00:00:50.617
&gt;&gt; David: She doesn't want to
pay a lot and really doesn't

00:00:50.617 --> 00:00:51.950
want a big debt.

00:00:51.950 --> 00:00:53.553
&gt;&gt; And how much was this one?

00:00:53.553 --> 00:00:56.522
&gt;&gt; David: Jenny is genuinely
looking to buy a car.

00:00:56.522 --> 00:00:57.890
&gt;&gt; Is it on?
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:00:57.890 --> 00:01:00.059
&gt;&gt; David: And recording it
all with hidden cameras...

00:01:00.059 --> 00:01:02.061
&gt;&gt; This will just
hide everything.

00:01:02.061 --> 00:01:05.231
&gt;&gt; David: ..'cause she
works for us.

00:01:05.231 --> 00:01:07.133
&gt;&gt; All right, see you later.

00:01:10.236 --> 00:01:12.772
&gt;&gt; David: About 2 million
new cars will be sold by the

00:01:12.772 --> 00:01:14.607
end of 2017.

00:01:14.607 --> 00:01:18.344
Many of them with the lure of
low payment loans that seem

00:01:18.344 --> 00:01:21.614 align:start position:0%
so affordable but are the
dealerships revealing everything

00:01:21.614 --> 00:01:24.117
you need to know?

00:01:24.117 --> 00:01:27.787
To find out,
we're calling in the pros.

00:01:27.787 --> 00:01:30.522
&gt;&gt; This car just turns
heads everywhere it goes.

00:01:30.522 --> 00:01:32.058
&gt;&gt; David: That's Shari Prymak.

00:01:32.058 --> 00:01:34.326
Mild-mannered
school teacher by day,

00:01:34.326 --> 00:01:37.363
car buying expert
in his free time.

00:01:37.363 --> 00:01:39.766
And that $100,000 Lexus?

00:01:39.766 --> 00:01:41.201
It's borrowed.

00:01:41.201 --> 00:01:44.503
&gt;&gt; I get to test drive
new cars every single week.

00:01:44.503 --> 00:01:46.472
I don't actually even own a car.

00:01:46.472 --> 00:01:48.775
&gt;&gt; David: Shari works
with Mohammed Bouchama.

00:01:48.775 --> 00:01:50.209
&gt;&gt; 84 months?

00:01:50.209 --> 00:01:52.078
&gt;&gt; David: He heads
Carhelp Canada .

00:01:52.078 --> 00:01:55.114
A popular car buying
service for consumers.

00:01:55.114 --> 00:01:57.383
&gt;&gt; Oh, yeah, they trust
what I tell them.

00:02:03.489 --> 00:02:06.859
&gt;&gt; David: They're dropping by
to analyse the financing advice

00:02:06.859 --> 00:02:09.294
Jenny's hearing at dealerships.

00:02:09.294 --> 00:02:10.430
&gt;&gt; Hi, David, good to meet you.

00:02:10.430 --> 00:02:11.430
&gt;&gt; David: Hi.

00:02:11.430 --> 00:02:14.300
Hi, Shari.
All right.

00:02:14.300 --> 00:02:15.567
We're going to look at some
clips.

00:02:15.567 --> 00:02:17.470
[ ♪♪ ]

00:02:18.737 --> 00:02:20.706
&gt;&gt; I'm looking
for a smaller car.

00:02:20.706 --> 00:02:23.977
&gt;&gt; David: Jenny's visiting ten
dealerships in the Toronto area

00:02:23.977 --> 00:02:28.414
that sell popular
small cars in Canada.

00:02:28.414 --> 00:02:32.317
She's barely in the door when
she hears about low payments

00:02:32.317 --> 00:02:34.787
spread over a very long time.

00:02:56.875 --> 00:03:01.347
&gt;&gt; David: That focus on payments
is a red flag for our experts.

00:03:01.347 --> 00:03:04.350 align:start position:0%
&gt;&gt; We don't even hear at all
the price of the vehicle at all.

00:03:04.350 --> 00:03:06.185
All we are getting is the
monthly payments or the weekly

00:03:06.185 --> 00:03:08.287
payments or the
biweekly payment.

00:03:08.287 --> 00:03:10.356
I mean, that's not right.

00:03:10.356 --> 00:03:11.623
It really is not at all.

00:03:11.623 --> 00:03:13.526
[ ♪♪ ]

00:03:19.699 --> 00:03:21.234
&gt;&gt; David: Over and over,
it's low payment...

00:03:31.377 --> 00:03:32.712
&gt;&gt; David: ..spread over
a long time.

00:03:35.080 --> 00:03:37.183 align:start position:0%
&gt;&gt; David: At most of the
dealerships they instantly offer

00:03:37.183 --> 00:03:42.555
up loans of seven years.

00:03:42.555 --> 00:03:44.724
&gt;&gt; And that's for seven years?
&gt;&gt; Seven years.

00:03:44.724 --> 00:03:46.926
&gt;&gt; The average consumer
sees that they think,

00:03:46.926 --> 00:03:48.160
"Oh, I can afford that car."

00:03:48.160 --> 00:03:50.162
"I can manage that, no problem."

00:03:50.162 --> 00:03:53.566
But it's just another way of
bringing consumers into the

00:03:53.566 --> 00:03:57.470
dealership and selling them
something that they really

00:03:57.470 --> 00:03:59.905
can't afford.

00:03:59.905 --> 00:04:01.574
&gt;&gt; David: Car loans
used to be shorter.

00:04:01.574 --> 00:04:02.842
Like 48 months.

00:04:02.842 --> 00:04:05.845
&gt;&gt; Get an incredibly low 2.9%
financing...

00:04:05.845 --> 00:04:07.480
&gt;&gt; David: Then came
the great recession.

00:04:07.480 --> 00:04:11.050
Money was tight so automakers
teamed up with banks and other

00:04:11.050 --> 00:04:15.688 align:start position:0%
lenders to get you buying again
by stretching out payments.

00:04:15.688 --> 00:04:18.657
&gt;&gt; Plus get zero percent
financing for 96 months.

00:04:18.657 --> 00:04:20.493
&gt;&gt; David: And it's working.

00:04:20.493 --> 00:04:23.630 align:start position:0%
More than half of new car
loans are seven years or longer.

00:04:36.575 --> 00:04:39.545
&gt;&gt; David: On nearly every visit,
Jenny is told paying off years

00:04:39.545 --> 00:04:41.047
early is no problem.

00:04:49.088 --> 00:04:51.523
&gt;&gt; David: Not true
according to our experts.

00:04:51.523 --> 00:04:53.692
&gt;&gt; I mean, yes,
you have the right to pay

00:04:53.692 --> 00:04:55.594
it off, but the majority of
people cannot afford to

00:04:55.594 --> 00:04:56.729
pay it off.

00:04:56.729 --> 00:04:57.864
&gt;&gt; David: And why is that?

00:04:57.864 --> 00:05:00.233
&gt;&gt; The majority of Canadians
are overloaded with debt.

00:05:00.233 --> 00:05:03.435
So really they can't
afford just to get suddenly,

00:05:03.435 --> 00:05:06.606
get $20,000 in one or two
years and pay off the car.

00:05:06.606 --> 00:05:07.873
It's impossible.

00:05:07.873 --> 00:05:10.275
&gt;&gt; David: Dealerships,
though, still suggest it,

00:05:10.275 --> 00:05:12.544
and seven out of
the ten Jenny visits,

00:05:12.544 --> 00:05:14.981
start by pushing long loans.

00:05:14.981 --> 00:05:17.316
&gt;&gt; They really should
be telling the shopper,

00:05:17.316 --> 00:05:19.384
"This is the price
of the vehicle."

00:05:19.384 --> 00:05:21.287
"These are your
different options."

00:05:21.287 --> 00:05:23.990
"You can finance for
this much over four years,

00:05:23.990 --> 00:05:26.291
"this much over five
years," and so on.

00:05:26.291 --> 00:05:28.528
&gt;&gt; David: So why
isn't that happening?

00:05:28.528 --> 00:05:31.297
Dealers and salespeople in
Ontario must follow a code of

00:05:31.297 --> 00:05:32.999
ethics and the law.

00:05:32.999 --> 00:05:35.835
They must be "clear",
"act with honesty, integrity".

00:05:35.835 --> 00:05:39.538
The man who enforces it
all is John Carmichael.

00:05:39.538 --> 00:05:40.973
We show him the offers.

00:05:40.973 --> 00:05:43.009
Low payments, long time

00:05:51.750 --> 00:05:58.157 align:start position:0%
&gt;&gt; That to me is short-sighted,
just a recipe for problems.

00:05:58.157 --> 00:06:00.826
For a consumer to make a fully
informed decision they need

00:06:00.826 --> 00:06:02.861
a lot more information
than that.

00:06:02.861 --> 00:06:05.164
&gt;&gt; David: Should a
potential buyer just be shown

00:06:05.164 --> 00:06:07.066
the long term options or
should they be told

00:06:07.066 --> 00:06:09.135
about other options
in front of them?

00:06:09.135 --> 00:06:10.569
&gt;&gt; Well, my preference
would be they should be

00:06:10.569 --> 00:06:12.438
shown all options.

00:06:12.438 --> 00:06:15.374
The more choices the better
able you are to make the best

00:06:15.374 --> 00:06:17.443
decisions for you
and your family.

00:06:17.443 --> 00:06:20.612 align:start position:0%
&gt;&gt; David: Jenny ended up pushing
 back a bit, against

00:06:20.612 --> 00:06:23.783
this idea of just the
seven year loan.

00:06:23.783 --> 00:06:24.850
&gt;&gt; Right.

00:06:24.850 --> 00:06:25.785
&gt;&gt; David: And I'd like to
show you a little bit of

00:06:25.785 --> 00:06:26.686
that discussion.

00:06:32.625 --> 00:06:35.394
&gt;&gt; David: Do you think that
advice is fair, is it honest?

00:06:35.394 --> 00:06:36.762
&gt;&gt; It's troubling.

00:06:36.762 --> 00:06:39.532
When I have a young person
who's standing in front of a

00:06:39.532 --> 00:06:41.367
situation like that,

00:06:41.367 --> 00:06:45.238
looking for their first car,
I would want to know they are

00:06:45.238 --> 00:06:48.373
getting a lot better
sales experience.

00:06:48.373 --> 00:06:51.677
I want to go in there and
find out what's going on.

00:06:51.677 --> 00:06:53.612
&gt;&gt; David: Shari has
his own theory.

00:06:53.612 --> 00:06:56.548 align:start position:0%
&gt;&gt; Long term loans with low
monthly payments often encourage

00:06:56.548 --> 00:07:00.652
consumers to buy a more
expensive car because why buy

00:07:00.652 --> 00:07:04.523
the affordable car for $20,000
when for a longer loan I can buy

00:07:04.523 --> 00:07:10.162
the fancier car for $30,000
at the same monthly payments?

00:07:10.162 --> 00:07:13.332
&gt;&gt; David: That is the key to
bigger revenue for automakers

00:07:13.332 --> 00:07:14.600
and dealers.

00:07:14.600 --> 00:07:18.371
While a $20,000 car costs
$154 every two weeks on a

00:07:18.371 --> 00:07:20.072
five year loan.

00:07:20.072 --> 00:07:24.744
A $30,000 car is just $11 more
a payment but you're paying for

00:07:24.744 --> 00:07:25.878
two more years.

00:07:33.719 --> 00:07:37.089
&gt;&gt; David: That upsell is
happening to Jenny right now

00:07:46.098 --> 00:07:50.536
[ Laughter ]

00:07:50.536 --> 00:07:51.904
&gt;&gt; This is the trick.

00:07:51.904 --> 00:07:54.006
Suddenly you stop
thinking about your budget,

00:07:54.006 --> 00:07:56.108
you stop thinking
what you can afford.

00:07:56.108 --> 00:07:59.178
And the way they
do it, well, don't worry.

00:07:59.178 --> 00:08:00.313
You can do it for 7 years.

00:08:00.313 --> 00:08:01.480
&gt;&gt; David: Yeah.

00:08:01.480 --> 00:08:03.149
&gt;&gt; And your monthly payments
going to be only this much!

00:08:24.670 --> 00:08:28.107
&gt;&gt; Cars are more complicated
now than they ever have been.

00:08:28.107 --> 00:08:29.708
There are a lot
more electronics,

00:08:29.708 --> 00:08:32.645
there are a lot more sensors,
there are a lot more sensitive

00:08:32.645 --> 00:08:35.848
parts that can be very
very costly to replace.

00:08:35.848 --> 00:08:38.384
&gt;&gt; The last thing you want to
do is be in a situation where

00:08:38.384 --> 00:08:40.852
you're making
payments on your vehicle,

00:08:40.852 --> 00:08:44.990
at 6th year or seventh year,
and it starts to require

00:08:44.990 --> 00:08:49.961
costly repairs, and at the same
time it's worth very little,

00:08:49.961 --> 00:08:51.697
if you want to sell the vehicle.

00:08:51.697 --> 00:08:54.000
&gt;&gt; David: In your opinion,
for the average person,

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:56.802
what is the best length
of time for a car loan?

00:08:56.802 --> 00:08:59.138
&gt;&gt; No more than five years.

00:08:59.138 --> 00:09:01.273 align:start position:0%
&gt;&gt; I would say ideally four
years but you can stretch it to

00:09:01.273 --> 00:09:02.475
five years.

00:09:02.475 --> 00:09:03.742
&gt;&gt; David: Seven and eight?

00:09:03.742 --> 00:09:04.744
&gt;&gt; No.

00:09:04.744 --> 00:09:05.977
&gt;&gt; No.
&gt;&gt; No, no, no.

00:09:05.977 --> 00:09:08.481
If you stretch the
loan to seven or eight,

00:09:08.481 --> 00:09:09.482
that means you
can't afford that car.

00:09:09.482 --> 00:09:11.350
&gt;&gt; Right.
&gt;&gt; Forget it.

00:09:11.350 --> 00:09:12.351 line:85%
&gt;&gt; David: Good advice.

00:09:12.351 --> 00:09:15.221 line:83%
And she does hear it,
only a couple of times.

00:09:20.058 --> 00:09:22.595
&gt;&gt; David: Even more rare,
sales people who warn

00:09:22.595 --> 00:09:23.696
about longer loans.

00:09:38.343 --> 00:09:40.479
&gt;&gt; That's great advice.

00:09:40.479 --> 00:09:41.547
It really is.

00:09:41.547 --> 00:09:42.582
I'm surprised actually.

00:09:42.582 --> 00:09:45.217
There is no question
he is telling her the truth,

00:09:45.217 --> 00:09:46.352
you know.

00:09:46.352 --> 00:09:48.054
&gt;&gt; David: This is what you
think people should be seeing.

00:09:48.054 --> 00:09:49.354
&gt;&gt; Absolutely.

00:09:49.354 --> 00:09:50.356
[ ♪♪ ]

00:09:50.356 --> 00:09:51.757
&gt;&gt; David:
Insider secrets...

00:09:51.757 --> 00:09:54.393 align:start position:0%
&gt;&gt; We'll give them enough
information to make a decision,

00:09:54.393 --> 00:09:56.728 align:start position:0%
but we're not going to point out
all the negatives.

00:09:56.728 --> 00:09:58.330
&gt;&gt; You're
not losing in any way.

00:09:58.330 --> 00:09:59.899
&gt;&gt; You're going
to lose your shirt.

00:09:59.899 --> 00:10:02.601
&gt;&gt; David: The ride continues
on your Marketplace.

00:10:02.601 --> 00:10:04.503
[ ♪♪ ]

00:10:06.538 --> 00:10:08.707
&gt;&gt; David: How not to buy a car.

00:10:08.707 --> 00:10:10.542
[ ♪♪ ]

00:10:10.542 --> 00:10:11.777
&gt;&gt; David: We're testing the
advice you get at dealerships

00:10:11.777 --> 00:10:13.613
about car loans.

00:10:19.651 --> 00:10:23.288
&gt;&gt; You can always
pay faster, it's an open loan.

00:10:23.288 --> 00:10:30.029 align:start position:0%
&gt;&gt; That to me is short-sighted,
just a recipe for problems.

00:10:30.029 --> 00:10:32.764
&gt;&gt; David: Problems leading many
Canadians into a spiral of debt

00:10:32.764 --> 00:10:34.532
they can't escape.

00:10:34.532 --> 00:10:36.435
[ ♪♪ ]

00:10:39.638 --> 00:10:41.707
&gt;&gt; David: 24-year-old
Chantelle Matthews knows

00:10:41.707 --> 00:10:43.075
all about it.

00:10:43.075 --> 00:10:47.780
She's working two jobs to
pay off one massive car loan.

00:10:47.780 --> 00:10:52.717
&gt;&gt; Basically, wake up,
go to work, and then go

00:10:52.717 --> 00:10:56.989
to the other job.

00:10:56.989 --> 00:11:00.159
&gt;&gt; David: Job #1, at a
building supply centre in

00:11:00.159 --> 00:11:04.129
Bracebridge, Ontario.

00:11:04.129 --> 00:11:06.932
She's here from seven to five.

00:11:06.932 --> 00:11:09.568
End of this shift is the
beginning of the next.

00:11:15.407 --> 00:11:17.243
How much sleep do you
usually get when you work

00:11:17.243 --> 00:11:18.610
two jobs like this?

00:11:18.610 --> 00:11:21.047
&gt;&gt; Between three to four hours.

00:11:21.047 --> 00:11:22.414
&gt;&gt; David: You must be
exhausted a lot of the time.

00:11:22.414 --> 00:11:24.549
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:11:24.549 --> 00:11:26.485
It does take a toll on you.

00:11:26.485 --> 00:11:31.156
&gt;&gt; David: Job #2
goes late, at the local pub.

00:11:31.156 --> 00:11:34.260
By the time she closes,
it's almost three am.

00:11:37.629 --> 00:11:39.532
[ ♪♪ ]

00:11:41.700 --> 00:11:44.302
&gt;&gt; David: Chantelle's troubles
began when she bought a new

00:11:44.302 --> 00:11:47.005
Hyundai on an eight year loan.

00:11:47.005 --> 00:11:49.141
[ ♪♪ ]

00:11:49.141 --> 00:11:52.210
&gt;&gt; I wanted a vehicle that was
cheap, reliable and

00:11:52.210 --> 00:11:55.447
you know, half decent, would
last you a while.

00:11:55.447 --> 00:11:58.951
&gt;&gt; $158 I believe
every two weeks. 

00:11:58.951 --> 00:12:03.422 align:start position:0%
&gt;&gt; David: Seemed affordable
but the car kept breaking down.

00:12:03.422 --> 00:12:06.692
&gt;&gt; The fan in the
fan motor went.

00:12:06.692 --> 00:12:09.895 align:start position:0%
The alternator went and the
wheel bearings started going and

00:12:09.895 --> 00:12:14.433 align:start position:0%
this is all within three months
of owning a brand new car.

00:12:14.433 --> 00:12:16.134
&gt;&gt; David: She says the
dealership wouldn't take

00:12:16.134 --> 00:12:17.202
it back.

00:12:17.202 --> 00:12:19.538
Told her to trade
it in for a new one.

00:12:19.538 --> 00:12:24.076
But the car was now worth much
less than she'd paid for it.

00:12:24.076 --> 00:12:27.947
&gt;&gt; They said you have to carry
some of it over because you

00:12:27.947 --> 00:12:29.181
signed for the car.

00:12:29.181 --> 00:12:30.783
The car has been used.

00:12:30.783 --> 00:12:33.252
&gt;&gt; David: That difference
between what she owed and what

00:12:33.252 --> 00:12:36.421
the car was worth is
called negative equity.

00:12:36.421 --> 00:12:38.090
&gt;&gt; It's not good.
&gt;&gt; Not good.

00:12:38.090 --> 00:12:41.961
It costs you and it
costs you big time.

00:12:41.961 --> 00:12:42.961
&gt;&gt; David: Sure does.

00:12:42.961 --> 00:12:46.332
It means $17,000 in
old debt was added to

00:12:46.332 --> 00:12:49.768
the loan for this new car.

00:12:49.768 --> 00:12:51.870
&gt;&gt; With the two cars,
it was about 50 grand.

00:12:51.870 --> 00:12:53.638
&gt;&gt; David: $50,000.

00:12:53.638 --> 00:12:55.541
&gt;&gt; Yup.

00:12:55.541 --> 00:12:57.743
&gt;&gt; David: You seem
very calm about that.

00:12:57.743 --> 00:13:01.546 align:start position:0%
